

1. What are User-Defined Annotations?

➡ Java gives us some built-in annotations.

➡ But we can also create our own custom annotations → these are called user-defined annotations.

➡ Useful when you want to give special meaning to your code for frameworks, tools, or custom processing.
👉 Think of them as labels you design yourself.


2. How to Create a User-Defined Annotation?

👉 Syntax:
@interface AnnotationName {
    // elements (optional)
}
Example (simple):
@interface MyAnnotation {
    String value(); // an element
}
Usage:
@MyAnnotation(value = "Hello")
class Test {}

3. Rules for User-Defined Annotations

* Use @interface keyword (not class or interface).

* Elements inside annotation look like methods, but they:
  ➡ Cannot have parameters.
  ➡ Cannot throw exceptions.
  ➡ Must have default values or must be provided when used.

* Allowed return types for elements:
  ➡ Primitive types (int, float, boolean, etc.)
  ➡ String
  ➡ Class
  ➡ enum
  ➡ Another annotation
  ➡ Arrays of above types


4. Annotation Elements Example

@interface MyAnnotation {
    int count();
    String message() default "Hello"; // default value
}

@MyAnnotation(count = 5)
class Test {}

👉 Here message is optional because it has a default value.